<i>Josse</i>), which in turn is from <i>Jodocus</i>, a Latinized form of a Breton name, <i>Iodoc</i>, meaning ‘lord’, borne by a 7th-century Breton saint. The name was in use in England among Breton followers of William the Conqueror. However, although this was fairly common as a male given name in the Middle Ages, it had virtually died out by the 14th century. There is evidence of its use as a girl's name from the 16th century onwards in parishes with strong Puritan links, which suggests that it may have been associated with the vocabulary word <i>joy</i>;  see  Joy .  It was strongly revived in the 19th century under the influence of popular fiction. It is borne by characters in Mrs  Henry Wood's  East Lynne (  1861 ) and  Edna Lyall's  In the Golden Days (  1885 ). Modern use may well have been influenced also by the common Irish surname derived from the medieval Norman male name.  See also  Joss ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Joyce Botetout was born in 1320, in Halesowen, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with Edward Burnel."},"et":{"1320–":"1320–Surnud","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1346–Female":"1346–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1346":"1346","1320":"1320","about 1346":"umbes 1346","Halesowen, Shropshire, England, Great Britain":"Halesowen, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Langley, Shropshire, England":"Langley and Ruckley, Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"1320–":"1320–Kuollut","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","1346–Female":"1346–Kuollut","1320–Female":"1320–Kuollut","1346":"1346","1320":"1320","about 1346":"noin 1346","Halesowen, Shropshire, England, Great Britain":"Halesowen, Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Langley, Shropshire, England":"Langley and Ruckley, Shropshire, England"},"fr":{"1320–":"1320–Décédée","1320–Male":"1320–Décédé","1346–Female":"1346–Décédée","1320–Female":"1320–Décédée","1346":"1346","1320":"1320","about 1346":"environ 1346","Halesowen, Shropshire, England, Great Britain":"Halesowen, S